In lesson2.5 -- Introduction to local scope, we noted that return by value creates a temporary object (holding a copy of the return value) that is passed back to the caller. When the return type and the return value are the same class type, the temporary object is initialized by implicitly invoking the copy constructor.For example:#include <iostream>

